      textEn: [
        "Zou Ji was over eight chi tall and of handsome appearance. One morning he dressed in his court robes and cap, looked in the mirror, and said to his wife: “Who is more handsome, I or Lord Xu of Chengbei?” His wife said: “You are far more handsome, my lord. How could Lord Xu compare with you?” Lord Xu of Chengbei was renowned throughout Qi for his good looks. Zou Ji did not believe her and asked his concubine the same question. His concubine said: “How could Lord Xu compare with you?” The next day, a guest came from outside, and while they sat talking, Zou Ji asked: “Who is more handsome, Lord Xu or I?” The guest said: “Lord Xu is not as handsome as you.” The following day, Lord Xu came to visit. Zou Ji looked him over carefully and felt he was indeed not as good-looking. He looked in the mirror and saw that the difference was actually quite large. That night, lying in bed and thinking it over, he said: “My wife says I am handsome because she is partial to me. My concubine says I am handsome because she fears me. My guest says I am handsome because he wants something from me.”",
        "Thereupon he went to court to see King Wei and said: “I know full well that I am not as handsome as Lord Xu. Yet my wife is partial to me, my concubine fears me, and my guest wants something from me—so they all told me I surpass Lord Xu. Now Qi has a thousand li of territory with a hundred and twenty cities. Among the palace women and attendants, none is not partial to the King. Among the court ministers, none does not fear the King. Within the four borders, none does not want something from the King. From this we can see: Your Majesty’s vision is severely obscured.”",
        "The King said: “Excellent.” He then issued an order: “All ministers and officials who can criticize my faults to my face shall receive the highest reward. Those who remonstrate in writing shall receive the middle reward. Those who discuss my faults in the marketplace so that I hear of it shall receive the lowest reward.” When the order was first issued, ministers came forward with advice and the court was as crowded as a marketplace. After several months, advice came only occasionally. After a full year, even those who wished to speak could find nothing more to say. The states of Yan, Zhao, Han, and Wei all came to pay court to Qi. This is what is called winning victory at court."
      ],
